      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Havana%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The railroad’s arrival in 1902 turned Havana into a shade‑tobacco hub, shipping 95 % of the country’s shade tobacco by the 1950s.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2,
        7,
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.florida-backroads-travel.com/havana-florida.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The historic Planters Exchange building, a National Historic Landmark, now hosts vendors, shops, and a museum that chronicles Havana’s tobacco legacy.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1,
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.florida-backroads-travel.com/havana-florida.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "In 1916 a fire destroyed 26 businesses, leaving only two stores, yet the town rebuilt and preserved its historic downtown.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Havana%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Havana’s motto, “Florida’s Friendliest Small Town,” reflects its reputation for welcoming visitors and maintaining quaint shops and restaurants.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
